h3. Issue Summary

When trying a migration into Cloud, the import fails at user migration phase if there's any user without the *externalId* property
h3. Steps to Reproduce

Make sure one or more users have a null *externalId* property.
 # Go to the source instance and null the external_id column of the cwd_user table for one user
 # Alternatively, remove the property from the XML entities.xml file 
 # Import into Cloud

*Invalid Example*
{code:java}
 <User id="16009" directoryId="1" userName="user A" lowerUserName="user a" active="0" createdDate="2014-05-22 21:29:11.0" updatedDate="2014-05-22 21:29:11.0" firstName="User" lowerFirstName="user" lastName="A" lowerLastName="a" displayName="usera" lowerDisplayName="usera" emailAddress="usera@email.com" lowerEmailAddress="usera@email.com" credential="nopass"/>{code}
*Valid Example*
{code:java}
 <User id="16009" directoryId="1" userName="user A" lowerUserName="user a" active="0" createdDate="2014-05-22 21:29:11.0" updatedDate="2014-05-22 21:29:11.0" firstName="User" lowerFirstName="user" lastName="A" lowerLastName="a" displayName="usera" lowerDisplayName="usera" emailAddress="usera@email.com" lowerEmailAddress="usera@email.com" credential="nopass" externalId="a5f77b4b04001c4a918f22b65aba6f30"/>{code}
h3. Expected Results

The ExternalIDs will be handled properly if it's missing or null
h3. Actual Results

Fails with the following error in the UI
 * Error importing data: cloud.atlassian.logmon.laas.api.PrivacySafeException: Privacy-safe boxing of a com.atlassian.crowd.exception.runtime.OperationFailedException

{noformat}
java.lang.NullPointerException: accountId
	at java.util.Objects.requireNonNull(Objects.java:290)
	at org.apache.commons.lang3.Validate.notBlank(Validate.java:440)
	at com.atlassian.jira.user.AccountId.<init>(AccountId.java:37)	
{noformat}
h3. Workaround

Add a dummy externalId property for each affected user that is *unique* for each user

To find broken users:
{code:java}
 grep "<User id=" ./entities.xml | grep -v "externalId="{code}
You can either update these users to include a proper externalId (dummy value) via the entities.xml or add a dummy value in the source instance:

 
{code:sql}
select * from cwd_user where directory_id = 1 and (external_id is null or external_id = ''){code}

h3. Issue Summary

During the attachment upload step, the migration fails with the error "*Request failed with code 401*". The attachment uploader throws the below exception.
{code:java}
2021-07-10 22:30:44,122 ERROR [pool-98-thread-4] [service.stepexecutor.attachment.AttachmentMigrationExecutor] error Attachment uploader finished with exception

java.util.concurrent.CompletionException: com.atlassian.migration.agent.okhttp.HttpServiceException: Bad request. Status code: 401, message: java.util.concurrent.CompletionException: com.atlassian.migration.agent.okhttp.HttpServiceException: Bad request. Status code: 401

2021-07-10 22:30:44,432 INFO [pool-98-thread-5] [service.stepexecutor.attachment.AttachmentsToMigrateConsumer] info Stop requested. Will exit...{code}
h3. Steps to Reproduce

This is not a regular error we observe during each Migration but have seen in a few MOVE tickets now.
 # Start a new Migration plan with CCMA for large space.
 # Migration fails with 401 error after some time.

h3. Expected Results

The migration should be successful.
h3. Actual Results

The below exception is thrown in the atlassian-confluence.log file:
{noformat}
2021-07-10 22:30:44,122 ERROR [pool-98-thread-4] [service.stepexecutor.attachment.AttachmentMigrationExecutor] error Attachment uploader finished with exceptionjava.util.concurrent.CompletionException: com.atlassian.migration.agent.okhttp.HttpServiceException: Bad request. Status code: 401, message: java.util.concurrent.CompletionException: com.atlassian.migration.agent.okhttp.HttpServiceException: Bad request. Status code: 401, message:  at java.util.concurrent.CompletableFuture.encodeThrowable(CompletableFuture.java:273) at java.util.concurrent.CompletableFuture.completeThrowable(CompletableFuture.java:280) at java.util.concurrent.CompletableFuture$AsyncRun.run(CompletableFuture.java:1629) at com.atlassian.migration.agent.logging.LoggingContextAwareExecutorService.lambda$execute$3(LoggingContextAwareExecutorService.java:104) at java.util.concurrent.ThreadPoolExecutor.runWorker(ThreadPoolExecutor.java:1142) at java.util.concurrent.ThreadPoolExecutor$Worker.run(ThreadPoolExecutor.java:617) at java.lang.Thread.run(Thread.java:745){noformat}
{noformat}
Caused by: com.atlassian.migration.agent.okhttp.HttpServiceException: Bad request. Status code: 401{noformat}
{noformat}
2021-07-10 22:30:44,432 INFO [pool-98-thread-5] [service.stepexecutor.attachment.AttachmentsToMigrateConsumer] info Stop requested. Will exit...{noformat}
h3. Workaround (With some stats please note the below steps may not work every time.)
 * Start a new migration plan with a new session by clicking on "*Choose cloud site*" and choosing the cloud site again.
 * Use incognito mode for Migration.
 * Delete the browser history as stated in this article [Cloud Assistance Not Working|https://confluence.atlassian.com/confkb/cloud-migration-assistant-not-working-1026058962.html]

 Imagine the following scenario: # Project {{A}} has 3 boards and it's migrated to cloud via transfer id {{X}}
 # Project {{B}} has 2 boards and it's migrated to cloud with transfer id {{Y}}

Now run this code:
this.accessor.getCloudMigrationGateway().getPaginatedMapping("Y", "jira/classic/software:rapidView", 100);
 
We expect to get only the mapping of 2 boards from project {{B}}. But, it returns all boards even from project {{A}}.
 
Instead, create a way to identify just the data from a specific transfer.

h3. Issue Summary

When calling
{code:java}
gateway.getCloudFeedback(transferId);
{code}
in Jira Cloud Migration Assistant, it always returns a HTTP 404. 

This works in Confluence Cloud Migration Assistant as expected.
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Implement {{onStartAppMigration()}} and call {{gateway.getCloudFeedback(transferId);}}

h3. Expected Results

If data is available then return feedback from app migration platform.
h3. Actual Results

HTTP 404 is always returned.

The below exception is thrown in the atlassian-jira.log file:
{noformat}
2021-06-24 14:00:47,036 Caesium-1-2 WARN ServiceRunner     [c.vendor.impl.MyPluginComponentImpl] getCloudFeedback error
[INFO] [talledLocalContainer] com.atlassian.jira.migration.httpclient.exceptions.UnexpectedStatusCodeException: Received an unexpected status code; expected [200], but received 404: {"timestamp":"2021-06-24T04:00:47.054Z","status":404,"error":"Not Found","message":"No message available","path":"/feedback/b5bf0d34-68ac-39fb-b03e-6a199b115eec"}
{noformat}
h3. Workaround

Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

h3. Issue Summary

The error message is a bit misleading in the following
{code:java}
"2021-06-21 14:12:20.379 ERROR XX project-export Board 'XXXXXXX' is referring to an in-existed saved filter ID: XXXXX. Configure an existing filter for this rapid view."{code}
h3. Expected Results

The error message should be changed to in-existed to non-existent to prevent confusion.
